In this code, applying the "Convert to interpolated string" refactoring:
```c#
struct ValueTuple<T>
{
    public T Item1;
    public T Item2;

    public override string ToString()
    {
        return "(" + Item1.ToString() + ", " + Item2.ToString();
    }
}
```
results in:
```c#
struct ValueTuple<T>
{
    public T Item1;
    public T Item2;

    public override string ToString()
    {
        return $"({Item1.ToString()}, {Item2.ToString()}";
    }
}
```
I think the `ToString` calls should be removed since they're unnecessary. They should also be removed in case of `Item1?.ToString()`.

**Version Used**: Visual Studio 2022 17.7.1, .NET Framework 4.7.2 & .NET 7.0


**Steps to Reproduce**:

1. Create readonly-lambda property, referencing a field, which has a holder property
2. Create lamba on a method of that property
3. Observe IDE0200, applying that consequently throws NullRef error, as that property hasn't been initialized yet

```
using System;

public class Repro
{
    private readonly Holder<External> holder;
    
    public External External => holder.Value;
    
    public Repro()
    {
        holder = new Holder<External>();
        Factory(() => External.Handler()); // IDE0200
        Factory(External.Handler); // NullReference Exception
    }
    
    private static void Factory(Action action)
    {
        // nop
    }
}

public class Holder<T>
{
    public T Value { get; set; }
}

public class External
{
    public void Handler()
    {
    }
}
```

