Found in preview 7, and @cston confirmed the behavior is a bug and is currently present in main.

```cs
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;

// Works
Enumerable.Any(["test"]);

// (Also: no errors below if the type of 'items' is changed to 'string[]')
IEnumerable<string> items = ["a", "b"];

// CS0411 The type arguments for method 'Enumerable.Any<TSource>(IEnumerable<TSource>)'
// cannot be inferred from the usage. Try specifying the type arguments explicitly.
Enumerable.Any(["test", ..items]);

// CS1950 The best overloaded Add method 'List<IEnumerable<string>>.Add(IEnumerable<string>)'
// for the collection initializer has some invalid arguments
// CS1503 Argument 1: cannot convert from 'string' to 'System.Collections.Generic.IEnumerable<string>'
Enumerable.Any([.. items]);

// Works
Enumerable.Any<string>(["test", .. items]);
Enumerable.Any<string>([.. items]);
```
